A DNA sequence is a string of base pairs (Adenine, Tyrosine, Cytosine, and Guanine) which, when arranged in triplets to form 'codons', create a DNA string which encodes polypeptides for a certain required task (intracellular or extracellular).

The DNA sequence has a start codon towards the 5' end, and a stop codon towards the 3' end, and the sequence between these codons is called the Open Reading Frame, which encodes a polypeptide.